>>47045069
I find plans counterproductive, myself, since no matter what plan I make, it never matches the surprises reality brings. So I end up being more productive without plans.

I think the most important step to finishing a project is to log out of all chats before working, rather than merely setting yourself to Away or Busy. For me, writing by hand, on paper, for the first draft was sometimes (but not always) useful. It's about distractions. You can multitask, but how well can you? If you aren't sublime at multitasking, consider not multitasking. Either be working or playing, but not both at the same time, unless you know it works for you.

A quote I find intriguing:
>In May 1963 Fleming wrote a piece for Books and Bookmen magazine in which he described his approach to writing Bond books: "I write for about three hours in the morning ... and I do another hour's work between six and seven in the evening. I never correct anything and I never go back to see what I have written ... By following my formula, you write 2,000 words a day."[157]
That's sort of what I attempt: write on paper without any checking at all, and only when I feel entirely finished for the day, I do preliminary markup on paper. I do the real checking after I type it out.

Well, to be sure, going out to the country on autumn weekends to hunt grouse used to be a pretty respectable upper-class WASP sort of hobby in the US. Guys would shoot a bunch of them and bring them back to have the chef cook them, maybe roast them wrapped in bacon with stuffing of wild rice and shallots, and eat them for dinner while drinking imported white wine and listening to opera on the hand-cranked wind-up record player that had the big paper horn for a speaker. Since around 1960 in the US hunting has gotten a lot less fashionable. So eating a grouse is not in and of itself horrifying. But being on a walk in the woods, suddenly jumping into the bushes and coming back with one in her mouth, with blood and feathers getting everywhere--that was genuinely really unsettling. I suppose the author wanted to remind us that Missy, on a very fundamental level, isn't a human in a fur suit.
